te:\n  - pc_0_0 ifconfig: eth0 up, IP 10.0.0.2/24, default gw 10.0.0.1.\n  - leaf_router_0_0 ifconfig: eth4 is 10.0.0.1/24 (correct gateway), routes and interface counters look normal (only 1 dropped RX reported).\n- qdisc / traffic control evidence:\n  - pc_0_0: \"qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%\" — netem configured with 60% corruption. (Observed output: qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%).\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (eth4): fq_codel shows no drops and normal counters.\n- BGP/FRR evidence:\n  - leaf_router_0_0: show ip bgp summary — all 4 spine neighbors established, prefixes received.\n  - spine and super-spine routers: sessions up, prefixes present, routes to 10.0.0.0/24 installed.\n\n4) Localization — likely faulty device(s)\n- Primary faulty device: pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2).\n  - Rationale: packet loss is concentrated toward this host, and the host itself shows a netem qdisc configured to corrupt 60% of packets — a direct and sufficient explanation.\n- Network devices (leaf/spine/super-spine routers): no evidence of BGP/session failures or interface errors across routers; routing to the 10.0.0.0/24 prefix is present and correctly advertised. Leaf router (10.0.0.1) shows expected connected route.\n\n5) Root-cause analysis\n- Direct cause: QoS/traffic-control impairment on pc_0_0. The netem qdisc on pc_0_0 is configured with \"corrupt 60%\" which will randomly corrupt (and effectively drop/unusable) roughly 60% of packets at the host’s egress/ingress depending on placement. This produces the observed asymmetric/intermittent packet loss when other hosts ping pc_0_0.\n- Contributing factors: none observed in the routing/control plane — BGP and inter-router links are stable and routes point correctly, so the impairment is local to the host.\n\n6) Confidence level\n- High confidence that pc_0_0’s netem corruption is the root cause of the observed packet loss. Evidence: direct tc/netem output showing corrupt 60% plus consistent ping-loss patterns to that specific IP, while router BGP and link counters are normal.\n\n7) Relevant raw findings (excerpts)\n- Reachability: multiple hosts report 25–75% packet loss when targeting 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0).\n- pc_0_0 tc/qdisc: \"qdisc netem ... corrupt 60%\".\n- leaf_router_0_0 ip route: 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected on eth4 (10.0.0.1).\n- FRR BGP summaries: all EBGP neighbors are established and advertising prefixes (no flaps or session issues observed).\n\n8) Suggested next diagnostic confirmations (no mitigation)\n- (If desired) run ping/traceroute from pc_0_0 toward multiple peers to characterize whether corruption affects egress, ingress, or both (to confirm directional behavior).\n- Inspect full tc qdisc configuration on pc_0_0 (tc qdisc show dev eth0) and any scripts that apply netem to determine why corruption was applied.\n- Gather packet captures at leaf_router_0_0 (eth4) and on pc_0_0 to confirm corrupted packets and check for retransmissions/ICMP errors.\n\nEnd of report.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 22331, "output_tokens": 2314, "total_tokens": 24645, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 0}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 960}}}
